location: Edmond, North-East OKC, Oklahoma City, Oklahoma
postcontent:
This is a pistol designed and originally manufactured by Beretta, but they sold the factory line to Stoeger a few years ago.

The specific model I have for sale is the Cougar 8000 FT, in 9mm.
It is one of the updated models with a rail (see pics).
In addition to the two 15-round factory mags (made in Italy), I have one 15-round Pro-mag for it (which has worked flawlessly).

I bought the pistol new on October 26th, and so it is barely 3 months old. I've taken it to the range about five times, and have shot approximately 300 rounds through it. It is in like-new condition and I've had no problems at all with it.

It has a 3.6" barrel, weights 32.6 oz, and has a very low recoil of 4.14 ft-lbs
See: http://www.genitron.com/Handgun/Stoe...9-mm/Variant-1

In my opinion (and why I bought it), it offers one of the very best combinations of size, weight and recoil -- especially for the money. I'm actually torn as to whether or not to sell it because I think its design is excellent. But I am not using it and promised my wife I would sell off a few pistols.

I have also modified the trigger, replacing the original mainspring to ease what was a very heavy pull. This, in my opinion, has resulted in an outstanding trigger, smooth & crisp. You can google "Cougar D spring" if you're curious about it.

Other features:
- all metal (though only 5oz more than Beretta's polymer PX4, what they moved to after selling the Cougar line).
- manual safety
- rotating barrel (improves accuracy and reduces felt recoil)
- stainless steel guide rod
- updated design with accessory rail
- original case & paperwork

Local price for the pistol is currently about $525 (incl. tax). Factor in the extra magazine, and we're at $550+.

Armslist & Gunbroker ads range from $400-$475 used (I'm adding an extra mag and this is the new model of the pistol, with a rail).

So, I'm listing it at $450 obo -- (cash only).  If you're short on ammo, I can sell you a couple of boxes with the pistol (50 rounds/box, 115 grain, FMJ, $15/box).

Face-to-face (I'm in Edmond but can also meet in OKC or Stillwater).

The only trade I would be interested in would be a Savage 93R17 BTV (or a different 93R17 model with a thumb-hole stock added).

title: For Sale:  5.56/.223 Remington
postcontent: Beware of people selling this ammo. It's either .223 OR 5.56, not both. 5.56 is a military round loaded to NATO specs. Which equates to higher pressures. It is NOT safe to fire in a gun chambered in .223 with a few rifles being exceptions. The throat is longer on a 5.56 rifle compared to a .223 chamber. The 223 is based on SAAMI specs aka lower pressures and shorter throat. You can safely fire .223 in a 5.56 chamber but generally not vice versa. Just a little info most people aren't aware of. Be safe!

title: For Sale:  LNIB Glock 29 Gen4 with accessories
postcontent:
Ok, I hate to have to do this but I am putting my LNIB Glock 29 Gen 4 10mm
pistol up for sale.

Since owning one several years ago, the Glock 29 has remained one of my favorite
pistols - real power in a compact size that fits my hand wonderfully and shoots
like a dream. It may not be everyone's cup of tea but I absolutely love 10mm!

I was ecstatic when a LEO friend offered to sell me his blue label Gen 4 Glock
29 last November. He had put less than 100 rounds through it and I have put
about the same so all told this beauty has seen less than 200 rounds down the
pipe. No hiccups. No malfunctions. Great stuff... FUN stuff!

As for mods, I had a local gunsmith install Warren Tactical fiber optic sights
but have otherwise left it stock.

In addition to the pistol with 3 mags and box with all standard accessories, I
am also including 5 additional 10-round mags (I hate loading mags at the range)
for a total of 8 mags, and 2 blue gun training mags (for safe dry fire and
reload practice.)

Now I'm sure you are asking "WTF! Why is he selling this?!?!" Well...

Unfortunately Uncle Sam came knocking with a fairly hefty tax bill this year
instead of the usual refund (the nerve of some people!) and I hate to say it but
I need to raise some money to make him go away. All told I have right at $850 in
this great package and that is what I need to get back out of it.

So, all of this goes to the first lucky person with $850 cash who can meet me
FTF in the Matthews NC area with a CCP or NC pistol purchase permit OR the first
person to say "That's mine now dude!" and pay the $850 plus shipping via PayPal
gift or money order to have this shipped to the FFL of their choosing.

I can tell you this: once the Uncle with his hand out is sent on his merry way
and I can save the funds, I will have another of these babies to carry in the
warmer weather. 

Until then, my hardship is your opportunity - don't let it pass you by!

As with our revolver Security System, the device is part of the firearm and cannot be lost, and the same special Security Key works for both the revolver and pistol Systems (two keys come with each gun). To engage: simply insert the Key into the button on the rear or side of the pistol and rotate one-quarter turn clockwise. This engages the Security System. The manual safety cannot be moved and the trigger cannot be pulled. To disengage: simply rotate the key one-quarter turn back. This releases the Security System, yet leaves the pistol's manual safety in the "safe" position until you are ready to release it yourself and fire the gun.

7 Rd Cylinder Feature
 Some Taurus models offer our 7-shot cylinder. A shot above the rest.

Transfer Bar
 The transfer bar mechanism prevents the hammer from striking the firing pin unless the trigger is pulled fully to the rear.
